The letter only professes to be one to inquire after Tibul- lus3 but occasion is taken to commend his fortunes and himself, and to bid him live every day as if it were the last. Horace writes to his friend (proba- bly from Rome).at his place near Pedum, a town of Latium, not far from · Praeneste. There Tibullus had a good estate, inherited from his father, which. before his death, 113 appears by some means to have diminished.
